      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In the acute phase, the neutrophils are the frontline demolition crew, moving into the site of infection to engulf and destroy the invaders—a process called phagocytosis. They are the immediate responders, deploying their toxic granules to kill bacteria right there on the spot. During a chronic infection, however, the lymphocytes take over the strategic planning. They are the long-term strategists, mounting an adaptive immune response, recognizing specific antigens, and orchestrating a sustained, targeted attack. The difference is speed versus precision.",
