    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "could u elaborate on the chemotaxis part? like what exactly triggers the movement of these cells to the site of injury or infection? i want to make sure i understand the signaling process.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Chemotaxis, the movement of these cells, is driven by chemical signals, which are essentially the scent trails left by the trouble. For neutrophils, the main triggers are chemokines—small signaling proteins that act like distress flares, telling the neutrophils exactly where the bacterial mess is. Think of it like a tiny, highly specific map drawn by the invading microbes. These chemokines bind to receptors on the neutrophil surface, initiating a cascade that tells the cell, \"Go *there*!\" This is a rapid, localized response, perfect for tackling an acute threat.",
      "source": "target",
